  "market_context": "NQ created high resistance liquidity by purging a prior high, while ES formed an SMT divergence at that same high showing relative weakness. Analyst switches to ES to map the next likely move using liquidity types and a nearby order block.",
  "key_observation": "ES is the weaker leg via SMT at the high, and a series of obvious equal/failure lows (low resistance liquidity) sits directly above a fair value gap with an order block — a clean liquidity-into-POI setup.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify the high resistance liquidity on NQ where the prior high was purged.",
    "Step 2: Note that ES failed to make a corresponding high, forming an SMT divergence and marking ES as the weaker asset.",
    "Step 3: Switch to the ES 60-minute chart to read the structure on the weaker leg.",
    "Step 4: Mark the series of obvious equal lows resting above a fair value gap as low resistance liquidity (the draw).",
    "Step 5: Identify the order block below those lows — formed when price reached into an important level and then a candle closed above, validating the OB.",
    "Step 6: Anticipate price to sweep the low resistance lows down into the order block's mean threshold for a reaction.",
    "Step 7: Project upside continuation: with all the lows swept and a series of lower highs stacked above, price is likely to reverse and trade back to those highs."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price ran the low resistance lows into the order block, reacted off its mean threshold, and reversed upward toward the stacked highs as anticipated.",
  "lessons": "Pair SMT divergence with liquidity classification: trade the weaker asset, target low resistance liquidity resting above a POI like an order block, and expect the mean threshold to deliver the reaction.",
